15 days of decluttering…15 minutes each day!🤍

All the way up until my birthday on December 15th!

We are starting with something easy… cleaning supplies!

Let’s narrow down what we have to what we actually use and have space for. Have multiple items that do the same thing? Choose the one that works best and get rid of the other. If it’s not a clear yes, then it’s a no-either toss it or donate it if you have somewhere you know of.

If possible, try to use a natural, non-toxic cleaner like @branchbasics that can have many purposes!

Wipe out any bins or cabinets that you keep your supplies in✔️

Put the items back that you are keeping and call it a day!

Day 9 of 15 days of decluttering…

Clothing is a struggle to declutter for most people. Here are a few questions to ask yourself:

-Would you buy this item again right now?
-Is the item in good condition?
-Does the clothing make you feel good when you wear it?
-Do you have duplicates? (Example: having 3 black cardigans or 5 pair of light jeans)

We wear 20% of our clothing 80% of the time. You probably already wear a minimal wardrobe but maybe have a lot of excess in your closet that will never be worn again. Why not declutter the items and focus on the pieces you love?

Today we tackle the bathroom! 

Do you have cabinets or drawers that are overflowing and hard to put things away?

Are you afraid to get rid of things because you spent a lot of money on them?

The first step in getting more minimal and having a more simple to clean home is making sure you have enough space to put everything away.

Grab a garbage bag and a donation box, be honest with yourself with items that you are never going to use. Aim to have your cabinets and drawers less than 50% full.

Tip: use an inexpensive bins under the sinks to group things together such as hair items and skin care items.

Take a look around and see if you have extra furniture, artwork, Knick knacks, table decor or rugs that don’t need to be there.

Remove items, even if temporarily, to see if less “visual clutter” makes your home feel more peaceful.

This is something I did with hundreds of people for my job as a home stager. Having less in a room almost always makes it feel bigger and more calm.

If a room feels overwhelming to you try…
✔️Having some blank walls
✔️Removing throw pillows and some blankets
✔️Less busy artwork especially word art
✔️Clear flat surfaces 

Remember everything in your home sends a message (vacuum me, dust me, update me etc)

Give it a try!

-80% of the clutter in most homes is a result of disorganization (because of too much to organize), not lack of space.

15 tiny tricks to reduce visual clutter ✔️

-Create a clutter drop zone (like a front closet for packages, bags that come in etc) 

-Use texture to decorate instead of more stuff 

-Neutrals simplify a space 

-Keep out only what you need (ex. You don’t need tons of throw blankets out at once)

-Hide electronics

-Keep spaces that you know will get messier out of main living space (ex. Craft room)

-Think about each rooms purpose (ex. Remove the excess)

-Use bigger pieces in a room instead of a bunch of little ones 

-No word signs (feels busy and the brain constantly reads them)

-Clear the front of the fridge

-Build in tidy sessions to the day

-Have a place for everything 

-Keep shoes out of sight in bins or on a shoe rack

-Make your bed every day (takes up a big area of your room visually)

-Touch up walls, fix broken items (our brains will always be looking to make a list of to do’s instead of relaxing)

Here is the real reason you have nothing to wear despite a closet full of clothes…

You need to declutter anything you won’t reach for to wear- this includes all the items that are stretched out, the wrong size, worn out, the wrong color on you, not flattering etc.

Most likely you are already only wearing a small percentage of your clothes.

Start over! Only put back what you absolutely will wear in the next 30 days- now donate/toss or pack away items that won’t be worn.

Small closet? Take occasional wear items OUT of your main closet and put in storage freeing up room.

We are always adding more to our homes and what if we actually really need is less…

Most of us are living with too many items to manage in the little time we have. The answer to curing the overwhelm and creating a home we can easily manage is to highly declutter and learn to live more simple.

There were way more than three BUT these are the top ones I want you to know so you don’t make them too…

1. The first mistake was trying to declutter everything at once. I thought that if I dedicated a whole weekend to decluttering my entire house, I could get it all done in one go. I needed to also change my mindset to focus on a simple home to keep it decluttered.

2. The second mistake made when decluttering is not having specific goals, which can result in getting rid of wanted items or keeping unnecessary things. To prevent this, set particular objectives for each decluttering session, such as decluttering the closet and keeping only clothes worn in the past year.

3. The third mistake I made was not having a system in place for disposing of unwanted items. I would often pile everything up in a corner of my room, with no plan for how to get rid of it. This resulted in cluttered piles taking up valuable space in my home.

My top 3 tips to get started decluttering + living simple…

1. **Start Small:** Begin by decluttering a small area, like a drawer or a shelf. This helps build momentum and confidence. Tackle one area at a time to prevent feeling overwhelmed.

2. **Identify Essentials:** Assess your belongings and determine what items are truly essential or bring you joy. If an item doesn’t serve a purpose or bring you happiness, consider letting it go.

3. **Establish Systems:** Create a system to maintain organization. Implement routines for regularly decluttering and designate spaces for items to prevent future accumulation of unnecessary things.
